In [[biochemistry]], the term '''sialome''' may refer to two distinct concepts:
* The set of [[messenger RNA|mRNA]] and [[protein]]s expressed in the [[salivary gland]]s, especially of [[mosquito]]es, [[tick]]s, and other [[hematophagy|blood-sucking]] arthropods.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Valenzuela | first = Jesus G. | title = Toward a description of the sialome of the adult female mosquito ''Aedes aegypti'' | journal = Insect Biochemistry and Molecular Biology | volume = 32 | issue = 9 |date=September 2002 | pages = 1101–1122 | doi = 10.1016/S0965-1748(02)00047-4 | pmid = 12213246|display-authors=etal}}</ref> * The total complement of [[sialic acid]] types and linkages and their modes of presentation on a particular [[organelle]], [[cell (biology)|cell]], [[tissue (biology)|tissue]], organ or organism - as found at a particular time and under specific conditions.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Varki | first = Ajit |author2=Takashi Angata | title = Siglecs—the major subfamily of I-type lectins | journal = Glycobiology | volume = 16 | issue = 1 | year = 2006 | pages = 1R–27R | doi = 10.1093/glycob/cwj008 | pmid = 16014749}}</ref>
